 ultimately lead to the U.S. Civil War. Taking a truly Atlantic perspective, Marques outlines the multiple forms of U.S. involvement in this traffic amid various legislation and shifting international relations, exploring the global processes that shaped the history of this participation.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSlave tradezAmericaxHistory. 0aSlave tradezAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistory. 0aSlave tradezBrazilxHistory. 0aSlave tradezCubaxHistory. 0aSlave tradezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSlave traderszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106677140 cprintz978030021241940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300224733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300224733/original  a978-3-11-066771-4  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles